        <p>
          In 2020 I founded <strong class="font-semibold text-ink">Force</strong>, a fitness center I grew to
          120+ members by treating it like a data problem: attendance, payments, retention, and churn all
          flowing into dashboards that actually drove decisions. That’s where I learned what most analysts
          learn late — that a metric only matters if it changes what someone does next.
        </p>
        <p>
          Today I’m an <strong class="font-semibold text-ink">Associate Data Warehouse Analyst at Assurant</strong>,
          on the Global Automotive Data team. My day is <strong class="font-semibold text-ink">SQL</strong>,
          <strong class="font-semibold text-ink">Excel</strong>, data modeling, and increasingly AI — turning raw,
          messy sources into a single version of the truth that business teams can trust.
        </p>
        <p>
          I’m also an early, hands-on adopter of <strong class="font-semibold text-ink">AI in analytics</strong> —
          using tools like Claude to draft and review SQL, automate the repetitive parts, and build small apps and
          data-backed business solutions. The strongest analysts of the next few years will be the ones who pair
          solid data fundamentals with AI as a force multiplier.
        </p>
        <p class="text-ink/60">Still learning every day — and enjoying every bit of it.</p>
